Structured bindings declares variables&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt; that bind to the members/elements of the thing being returned.  That means you can&#39;t use `std::ignore` since for one it is not a valid variable name and for two it is a name that has apready been declared.  If you want to ignore the result, just name the member `ignore` and don&#39;t use it like

	for(auto [camera, ignore]: landmark-&gt;getObservations())
		camerasToCounts[camera]++;
		
---

1: It actually only creates a single variable that the return value is stored in and then the names in the square brackets are actually references the ith member of the returned object.

