- in the base `operator&lt;&lt;`, the `Animal` parameter is being passed as a non-`const` reference.  It should be a `const` reference instead.

- in the derived `operator&lt;&lt;`:

 - the `Bird` parameter is being passed by value, not by a `const` reference.

 - you are trying to call your base `operator&lt;&lt;` using a `const Animal*` pointer, but there is no overload of `operator&lt;&lt;` that takes a `const Animal*` pointer as input.  There is, however, an `operator&lt;&lt;` in the `std:::ostream` class that takes a `const void*` as input, and all pointer types are implicitly convertible to `void*` (that operator simply prints out the memory address that the pointer is pointing to).  Since your base `operator&lt;&lt;` takes an `Animal&amp;` reference, you need to pass your `Bird` object to it as an `Animal&amp;` reference rather than as an `Animal*` pointer.

Try this instead:

```c++
ostream&amp; operator&lt;&lt;(ostream &amp;os, const Animal &amp;animal) {
    ostringstream oss;

    oss &lt;&lt; &quot;Id: &quot; &lt;&lt; animal.Id
        &lt;&lt; &quot;\nAge: &quot; &lt;&lt; animal.age
        &lt;&lt; &quot;\nStatus: &quot; &lt;&lt; animal.status
        &lt;&lt; &quot;\nLocation: &quot; &lt;&lt; animal.locX &lt;&lt; &quot;, &quot; &lt;&lt; animal.locY;

